You found it. The `--debug` log is conclusive, and your reading is exactly right. This is the line that solves the entire week of debugging:

```
[org.apache.http.impl.execchain.MainClientExec] Opening connection
  {tls}->http://serverswg.sbi.co.in:9090->https://artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443

[org.apache.http.impl.conn.DefaultHttpClientConnectionOperator]
  Connecting to serverswg.sbi.co.in/10.191.191.39:9090

[org.apache.http.impl.execchain.MainClientExec]
  CONNECT refused by proxy: HTTP/1.1 503 Service Unavailable
```

Gradle's JVM is routing the Artifactory request **through an HTTP proxy `serverswg.sbi.co.in:9090`**, that proxy answers `503`, and Gradle then reports the misleading `Plugin not found`. The artifact is fine, the repo is fine, the credentials are fine, TLS is fine. The JVM just shouldn't be using a proxy at all to reach an on-LAN host — and the bastion curl worked precisely because curl had no proxy set.

## Where the proxy comes from

The JVM picks up proxy settings from one of these, in this image/environment:
1. `JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS` / `GRADLE_OPTS` containing `-Dhttp(s).proxyHost`
2. Environment variables `http_proxy` / `https_proxy` / `HTTP_PROXY` / `HTTPS_PROXY`
3. A baked-in default in the image (your inspect didn't show proxy env, so it's most likely injected as a CI/CD variable or a `gradle.properties` in `GRADLE_HOME`)
4. `/opt/gradle/gradle.properties` or `~/.gradle/gradle.properties` with `systemProp.https.proxyHost=…`

The route string `{tls}->http://serverswg.sbi.co.in:9090->https://artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443` is Apache HttpClient's way of saying "tunnel HTTPS through this HTTP proxy." So a proxy is definitely configured somewhere the JVM reads.

## Step 1 — Find where it's set (run inside the image)

```bash
podman run --rm -it \
  artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443/itepaypg-sbiepay2-docker-local/custom-ci/gradle-8.9-jdk-21:v9 \
  bash -lc '
    echo "=== ENV PROXIES ==="; env | grep -i proxy
    echo "=== GRADLE_OPTS ==="; echo "$GRADLE_OPTS"
    echo "=== JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS ==="; echo "$JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS"
    echo "=== /opt/gradle/gradle.properties ==="; cat /opt/gradle/gradle.properties 2>/dev/null
    echo "=== ~/.gradle/gradle.properties ==="; cat ~/.gradle/gradle.properties 2>/dev/null
    echo "=== JVM net props file ==="; cat "$JAVA_HOME/conf/net.properties" 2>/dev/null | grep -i proxy
  '
```

One of these will show `serverswg.sbi.co.in:9090`. That's your culprit. (Also check the GitLab project/group CI/CD variables for `https_proxy` / `HTTPS_PROXY` — GitLab injects those into the job environment and the JVM honors them.)

## Step 2 — Bypass the proxy (pick based on what Step 1 finds)

You don't need to rebuild the image. The cleanest fix is to tell the JVM not to proxy Artifactory. Three options, best first:

**Option A — `nonProxyHosts` (surgical, keeps proxy for anything that needs it):**

Add to `GRADLE_OPTS` in your `.build` job variables:

```yaml
variables:
  GRADLE_OPTS: >-
    -Dorg.gradle.daemon=false
    -Dhttp.nonProxyHosts=artifactory.jfrog.sbi|gitlab.sbi|*.sbi
    -Dhttps.nonProxyHosts=artifactory.jfrog.sbi|gitlab.sbi|*.sbi
```

Note: `nonProxyHosts` uses `|` separators and applies to both http and https when set as `http.nonProxyHosts` (the `https.` variant isn't standard but harmless to include).

**Option B — kill the proxy entirely for the job (simplest, if nothing in CI legitimately needs the proxy in an air-gapped env):**

```yaml
variables:
  GRADLE_OPTS: "-Dorg.gradle.daemon=false -Dhttp.proxyHost= -Dhttps.proxyHost="
  http_proxy: ""
  https_proxy: ""
  HTTP_PROXY: ""
  HTTPS_PROXY: ""
  no_proxy: "artifactory.jfrog.sbi,gitlab.sbi,.sbi,localhost,127.0.0.1"
  NO_PROXY: "artifactory.jfrog.sbi,gitlab.sbi,.sbi,localhost,127.0.0.1"
```

In an air-gapped environment you almost certainly want **no proxy at all** — there's nothing outside to proxy to. So unsetting it wholesale is reasonable.

**Option C — explicitly null the proxy in the init script** (if it's baked into a `gradle.properties` you can't easily remove). Add to `before_script` before the build:

```bash
- |
  cat >> "${GRADLE_USER_HOME}/gradle.properties" <<EOF
  systemProp.http.proxyHost=
  systemProp.https.proxyHost=
  systemProp.http.nonProxyHosts=*
  systemProp.https.nonProxyHosts=*
  EOF
```

`nonProxyHosts=*` tells the JVM "never proxy anything," which in an air-gapped LAN is exactly what you want.

## Step 3 — Verify the fix before the full build

Add a one-line probe to `before_script` so you confirm the route is now direct:

```bash
- |
  curl -s -o /dev/null -w "DIRECT-CURL: %{http_code}\n" \
    --noproxy '*' -u "$JF_USER:$JF_TOKEN" \
    "https://artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443/artifactory/itepaypg-sbiepay2-gradle-virtual/org/springframework/boot/org.springframework.boot.gradle.plugin/3.5.9/org.springframework.boot.gradle.plugin-3.5.9.pom"
```

Expect `200`. Then run the Gradle build; the `Opening connection` line in debug should now read a **direct** route to `artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443` with no `serverswg` hop.

## Important secondary note on your current `.build` config

You switched the TLS approach to:

```bash
cp "$ARTIFACTORY_CERT" /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/jfrog-internal.crt
update-ca-trust extract
```

That's actually a cleaner approach than the per-job keystore copy — `update-ca-trust` updates the OS bundle, and on UBI9 the JVM cacerts is wired to it. The debug log confirms TLS trust is now working (you can see the full SBI cert chain `SBI-CA → SBI-RCA` being evaluated and accepted before the proxy `503`). So keep this. The proxy is the only remaining blocker.

Also note the credential format the JVM is using — the debug shows it trying **NTLM** first:

```
Using Credentials [username: [MASKED]] ... using NTLM
```

That's a side effect of the proxy negotiation, not your Artifactory creds. Once the proxy is bypassed, that NTLM attempt disappears. No action needed beyond removing the proxy.

## Why "it worked on 9.4"

Now fully explained: the 9.4 image (or an earlier runner) either had `nonProxyHosts` set, no proxy configured, or ran on a runner network where `serverswg` happened to forward correctly. The `v9`/`24062026`/`v6` images inherit a proxy setting that points at `serverswg.sbi.co.in:9090`, which returns `503` for the Artifactory CONNECT. The Gradle version was never the issue — the proxy configuration differs between images.

## Summary

- **Root cause:** JVM routes Artifactory traffic through proxy `serverswg.sbi.co.in:9090`, which refuses the tunnel with `503`. Gradle masks this as `Plugin not found`.
- **Fix:** bypass the proxy for the build — `nonProxyHosts` (Option A) or unset proxy env entirely (Option B). In an air-gapped LAN, Option B / `nonProxyHosts=*` is the right default.
- **Everything else is sound:** version 3.5.9 exists, the marker is served (`200`), credentials work, TLS trust via `update-ca-trust` works, Gradle 8.9 is fully compatible with your stack.

